<hr />

<p>Mascots are not branding. They are <strong>debug symbols with feelings</strong> — records of how a system broke in public and the face it wore while doing it. Names wobble. Failure signatures stay consistent.</p>

<p>Each entry encodes a mascot's <strong>failure shape</strong>: the specific category of wrongness it belongs to, which Lorelog cases called it forth, and which layers of the archive it haunts.</p>

<p>If you see the same <code>mascotRef</code> across multiple case files, assume the same category of problem is trying to get your attention.</p>

<h2>Taxonomy</h2>

<p>Descriptive, not authoritative. Mascots cross boundaries when failure types start to rhyme.</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Navigation Ghosts</strong> — missing pages, dead links, feelings with nowhere to go. (404sy McLostalot)</li>
  <li><strong>Continuity Clerks</strong> — continuity breaches, uptime theatre, over-filed contradictions. (Bricky Goldbricksworth)</li>
  <li><strong>Emotional Liaisons</strong> — emotional overflow, meta-feelings, intake spiral. (Kindy McExistentialCrisis)</li>
  <li><strong>Protocol Spirits</strong> — thermal events, HTTP status theatre, form-bound behavior. (Boily McPlaterton, Teapotta Protocol)</li>
  <li><strong>Morale &amp; Metrics Entities</strong> — fake kindness, gratitude graphs, comfort without change. (Serotonin Sam)</li>
  <li><strong>Archive-Aligned Weirdos</strong> — consent loops, opt-out failures, narrative survival. (Friendrick the Extant)</li>
</ul>

<h2>Behavioral Rules</h2>

<ol>
  <li>Mascots are failure signatures. They must remain attached to specific kinds of wrongness.</li>
  <li>No new mascot without at least one Lorelog case proving which failure it belongs to.</li>
  <li>A mascot may change aesthetics. It may not change its failure domain without filing an identity drift incident.</li>
  <li>If UI copy treats a mascot as a cheerleader rather than a witness, the archive may repossess it.</li>
  <li>Mascot frontmatter is canon for where that ghost is allowed to appear.</li>
</ol>

